Section 1

Why the Temperature Anomalies Data set?

The data set I have taken up is the Temperature Anomalies Data set . This data set has been sourced by National Centers for Environmental Information who publish it on a monthly basis. I have always been fascinated by how trivial we are in the grand scheme of things, rising temperatures globally are proof of the fact that our lives are defined by the world around us and we need to respect what is out there to survive and this led me to choose this data set as it will help forecast what is ahead.

Data Generating Process:

The data generating process is handled by National Centers for Environmental Information or NOAA . The data is calculated every month by observing the rise in temperature on both ground and sea level.Considering that global rise in temperature depends on factors beyond our control , it is a variable that is difficult to predict or forecast.

Data Source https://www.ncei.noaa.gov/access/monitoring/climate-at-a-glance/global/time-series

Section 3

Moving Averages

After filtering our data, we visualize the moving averages with different orders to gain further insight into our time series data. As we know moving averages average values from a window of consecutive time periods, thereby generating a series of averages. Though logically as the the order increases the curve tends to get smoother and that is what has been observed in our plot we cannot ignore the structure of data while choosing which moving average order to consider for our data. Assuming that the temperature changes increase/decrease roughly in a consistent way throughout a single year, the order 13 moving average seems to fit the data better.

Code 
library(zoo)
library(feasts)
data_monthly %>%
    filter(Year>='2010-01-01') %>%
    mutate(year_moving_average = rollmean(Value,13,na.pad=T)) %>%
    ggplot()+
    geom_line(aes(Year,Value,group=1))+
    geom_line(aes(Year,year_moving_average,group=1),color='blue')
Code 
library(zoo)

 # Adding the multi order
 d1new <- data_monthly %>%

   ))

Moving Averages Analysis on our data :

In this step of our analysis, we subtract the moving average trend from our original time series data, in an ideal scenario our remainder should be just white noise as in there should not be any inherent patterns in our remainder plot . But considering that in our plot below , we observe a pattern in our remainder plot , as in our white noise is not random and seems to have some evident pattern in it. This shows us that seasonality in our data is evident and appears to be strong.

Code 
Temp_decomp <- data_monthly %>%
mutate(
 ma_13_centre = rollapply(Value, 13, FUN = mean, align = "center", fill = NA)
 ) %>%
 mutate(resid = Value - ma_13_centre) %>%
 select(Year, Value, ma_13_centre, resid)

Temp_decomp_plot <- Temp_decomp %>%
 pivot_longer(
 Value:resid,
 names_to = "decomposition",
 values_to = "Value"
 ) %>%
 mutate(
 decomposition = case_when(
 decomposition == "Value" ~ "Temp Anomalies",
 decomposition == "ma_13_centre" ~ "Trend",
 decomposition == "resid" ~ "Remainder"
 )
 ) %>%
 mutate(
 decomposition = factor(
 decomposition,
 labels = c(
 "Temp Anomalies",
 "Trend",
 "Remainder"
 ),
 levels = c(
 "Temp Anomalies",
 "Trend",
 "Remainder"
 )
 )
 ) %>%
 ggplot() +
 geom_line(aes(Year, Value), size = 1) +
 facet_wrap(
 ~decomposition,
 nrow = 3,
 scales = "free"
 ) +
 theme_bw() +
 ylab("") +
 xlab("YEAR") +
 ggtitle(
    "Temp Anomalies = Trend + Remainder"
  )

Seasonality in our data :

Visualizing the lag plots shows us that there is correlation between remainder and remainder (lag) which implies that there is autocorrelation in the remainder.This means that the remainder can be interpreted in some manner using the past remainder. This supports our earlier argument about white noise having some seasonality in it. But this not a sure shot confirmation of existence of seasonality since it is known that decomposition model outputs a seasonality even when there isnât one in the time series.

Code 
data_decomp_lag <- Temp_decomp %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), list(lag = lag))) %>%
  select(
    Year, Value, Value_lag,
    ma_13_centre, ma_13_centre_lag, resid, resid_lag
  ) %>%
  drop_na()

cor_value <- round(cor(data_decomp_lag$Value, data_decomp_lag$Value_lag), 2)
cor_ma <- round(cor(data_decomp_lag$ma_13_centre_lag, data_decomp_lag$ma_13_centre), 2)
cor_resid <- round(cor(data_decomp_lag$resid_lag, data_decomp_lag$resid), 2)

value_plot <- data_decomp_lag %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(Value_lag, Value)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(Value_lag, Value), method = "lm", se = F) +
  labs(
    title = "Temp Anomalies ",
    subtitle = paste("Cor = ", cor_value)
  ) +
  theme_bw()+
  ylab('Temp Anomalies')+
  xlab('Temp Anomalies (Lag)')

ma_13_centre_plot <- data_decomp_lag %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(ma_13_centre_lag, ma_13_centre)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(ma_13_centre_lag, ma_13_centre), method = "lm", se = F) +
  labs(
    title = "Moving Average",
    subtitle = paste("Cor = ", cor_ma)
  ) +
  theme_bw()+
  ylab('Moving Average')+
  xlab('Moving Average (Lag)')

resid_plot <- data_decomp_lag %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(resid_lag, resid)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(resid_lag, resid), method = "lm", se = F) +
  labs(
    title = "Remainder",
    subtitle = paste("Cor = ", cor_resid)
  ) +
  theme_bw()+
  ylab('Remainder')+
  xlab('Remainder (Lag)')

value_plot + ma_13_centre_plot + resid_plot
Code 
Temp_decomp %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  mutate(Year = yearmonth(Year))%>%
  gg_lag(resid, geom = "point", lags = 1:15, ) +
  geom_smooth(aes(color=NULL),method='lm',color='red',se=F) +
  labs(title="Lag Plot of the residuals to test seasonality")

The below is what we observe in our time series data set after classical decomposition : From the lag plots we can see that the correlation is present, we have decomposed the time series data using classical decomposition and we can see the presence of seasonality our time series data.

Code 
data_monthly %>%

data_monthly %>%
   mutate(Year = yearmonth(Year)) %>%

Section 4

FORECASTS

Naive forecasting is basically taking the last value in our data to predict our next value. Naive forecasts work for data when there is no presence of seasonality but considering that there is seasonality in our data we are better off using a Seasonal naive forecast to get a more accurate forecast. The forecasts below are made for the next 6 periods as in 6 months in our case.

Code 
data_monthly %>%
  mutate(Year = yearmonth(Year)) %>%
          as_tsibble(index = Year) %>%
  model(
    Naive = NAIVE(Value)
  ) %>%
  forecast(h = 6) %>%
  autoplot(data_monthly, level = NULL,size=1) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = ymd("2022-12-01")), color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +
  theme_bw()+
  ylab('Temp Anomalies')

Seasonal data seems to work well with our data as it takes seasonality into account while forecasting our value and since temperature anomalies are unpredictable this could be useful.

Code 
data_monthly %>%
  mutate(Year = yearmonth(Year)) %>%
          as_tsibble(index = Year) %>%
  model(
    Naive = SNAIVE(Value)
  ) %>%
  forecast(h = 6) %>%
  autoplot(data_monthly, level = NULL,size=1) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = ymd("2022-12-01")), color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +
  theme_bw()+
  ylab('Temp Anomalies')
